     1тЖТ# The clean command
     3тЖТThe clean command is used to delete the generated book and any other build
     4тЖТartifacts.
     5тЖТ
     6тЖТ```bash
     7тЖТmdbook clean
     8тЖТ```
     9тЖТ
    10тЖТ#### Specify a directory
    19тЖТ#### `--dest-dir`

completions.md
     1тЖТ# The completions command
     3тЖТThe completions command is used to generate auto-completions for some common shells.
     4тЖТThis means when you type `mdbook` in your shell, you can then press your shell's auto-complete key (usually the Tab key) and it may display what the valid options are, or finish partial input.
     5тЖТ
     6тЖТThe completions first need to be installed for your shell:
     7тЖТ
     8тЖТ```bash
     9тЖТ# bash
    10тЖТmdbook completions bash > ~/.local/share/bash-completion/completions/mdbook
    11тЖТ# oh-my-zsh
    12тЖТmdbook completions zsh > ~/.oh-my-zsh/completions/_mdbook
    13тЖТautoload -U compinit && compinit
    14тЖТ```
    15тЖТ
    16тЖТThe command prints a completion script for the given shell.
    17тЖТRun `mdbook completions --help` for a list of supported shells.
    18тЖТ
    19тЖТWhere to place the completions depend on which shell you are using and your operating system.
    20тЖТConsult your shell's documentation for more information one where to place the script.

init.md
     1тЖТ# The init command
     3тЖТThere is some minimal boilerplate that is the same for every new book. It's for
     4тЖТthis purpose that mdBook includes an `init` command.
     5тЖТ
     6тЖТThe `init` command is used like this:
     7тЖТ
     8тЖТ```bash
     9тЖТmdbook init
    10тЖТ```
    11тЖТ
    12тЖТWhen using the `init` command for the first time, a couple of files will be set
    13тЖТup for you:
    14тЖТ```bash
    15тЖТbook-test/
    16тЖТтФЬтФАтФА book
    17тЖТтФФтФАтФА src
    18тЖТ    тФЬтФАтФА chapter_1.md
    19тЖТ    тФФтФАтФА SUMMARY.md
    20тЖТ```
    21тЖТ
    22тЖТ- The `src` directory is where you write your book in markdown. It contains all
    23тЖТ  the source files, configuration files, etc.
    24тЖТ
    25тЖТ- The `book` directory is where your book is rendered. All the output is ready
    26тЖТ  to be uploaded to a server to be seen by your audience.
    27тЖТ
    28тЖТ- The `SUMMARY.md` is the skeleton of your
    29тЖТ  book, and is discussed in more detail [in another
    30тЖТ  chapter](../format/summary.md).
    31тЖТ
    32тЖТ#### Tip: Generate chapters from SUMMARY.md
    39тЖТ#### Specify a directory
    48тЖТ#### `--theme`
    56тЖТ#### `--title`
    65тЖТ#### `--ignore`
    80тЖТ#### `--force`

serve.md
     1тЖТ# The serve command
     3тЖТThe serve command is used to preview a book by serving it via HTTP at
     4тЖТ`localhost:3000` by default: 
     5тЖТ
     6тЖТ```bash
     7тЖТmdbook serve
     8тЖТ```
     9тЖТ
    10тЖТThe `serve` command  watches the book's `src` directory for
    11тЖТchanges, rebuilding the book and refreshing clients for each change; this includes
    12тЖТre-creating deleted files still mentioned in `SUMMARY.md`! A websocket
    13тЖТconnection is used to trigger the client-side refresh.
    14тЖТ
    15тЖТ***Note:*** *The `serve` command is for testing a book's HTML output, and is not
    16тЖТintended to be a complete HTTP server for a website.*
    17тЖТ
    18тЖТ#### Specify a directory
    27тЖТ### Server options
    29тЖТThe `serve` hostname defaults to `localhost`, and the port defaults to `3000`. Either option can be specified on the command line:
    30тЖТ
    31тЖТ```bash
    32тЖТmdbook serve path/to/book -p 8000 -n 127.0.0.1 
    33тЖТ```
    34тЖТ
    35тЖТ#### `--open`
    40тЖТ#### `--dest-dir`
