test.md
     1тЖТ# The test command
     3тЖТWhen writing a book, you sometimes need to automate some tests. For example,
     4тЖТ[The Rust Programming Book](https://doc.rust-lang.org/stable/book/) uses a lot
     5тЖТof code examples that could get outdated. Therefore it is very important for
     6тЖТthem to be able to automatically test these code examples.
     7тЖТ
     8тЖТmdBook supports a `test` command that will run all available tests in a book. At
     9тЖТthe moment, only Rust tests are supported.
    10тЖТ
    11тЖТ#### Disable tests on a code block
    31тЖТ#### Specify a directory
    40тЖТ#### `--library-path`
    57тЖТ#### `--chapter`

watch.md
     1тЖТ# The watch command
     3тЖТThe `watch` command is useful when you want your book to be rendered on every
     4тЖТfile change. You could repeatedly issue `mdbook build` every time a file is
     5тЖТchanged. But using `mdbook watch` once will watch your files and will trigger a
     6тЖТbuild automatically whenever you modify a file; this includes re-creating
     7тЖТdeleted files still mentioned in `SUMMARY.md`!
     8тЖТ
     9тЖТ#### Specify a directory
    18тЖТ#### `--open`
    23тЖТ#### `--dest-dir`
    32тЖТ#### Specify exclude patterns
